<P>Here Mr. <HI>Tilghman</HI> ob&s;erved that Mr. <HI>Nichol&s;on</HI> was &s;till of the &s;ame opinion, and that before the time of pa&s;&s;|ing the Act of 10th April, 1792, he propo&s;ed a plan in oppo&s;ition to that Act, in which he included New-Loans as a &s;tate debt as follow&mdash;</P>
<P>(A.) "A plan for modifying the pre&s;ent debt of <HI>Penn&s;ylvania.</HI></P>
<P>"WHEREAS the Commonwealth and the creditors may be reciprocally benefited by a communication of the debt in manner hereinafter provided: it is propo&s;ed.</P>
<P>(B.) "That be&s;ide the provi&s;ion for payment of the debt by parting with the &s;tock of the United States, the property of this State, the creditors may at their option &s;ub&s;cribe their debts to the following loan hereby pro|po&s;ed.</P>
<P>"That the &s;tock thereby created &s;hall bear an inter|e&s;t of &s;ix per cent per annum, commencing July 1&s;t, 1792, payable quarter yearly, that is to &s;ay on the 2d days of January, April, July, and October in every year.</P>
